<DocsLayout
  title="Canvas - Arris Docs"
  breadcrumbs={[{ label: "Docs", href: "/" }, { label: "AI" }, { label: "Canvas" }]}
  heading="Canvas"
  lede="A visual board where you chat with an AI agent that reads your schema and builds analytics objects for you: a query that runs, a chart of its results, and text that explains them."
  tocItems={[
    { label: "What the canvas is", href: "#overview" },
    { label: "Opening a canvas", href: "#opening" },
    { label: "Objects", href: "#objects" },
    { label: "Building with the agent", href: "#agent" },
    { label: "Working on the board", href: "#board" },
    { label: "Saving", href: "#saving" },
  ]}
  currentPath="/ai/canvas"
  prev={{ label: "AI Agent", href: "/ai/agent", section: "AI" }}
  next={{ label: "Keyboard shortcuts", href: "/reference/shortcuts", section: "Reference" }}
>
  <h2 id="overview">What the canvas is</h2>

  <p>
    The canvas is an infinite, freeform board (pan, zoom, and drag) where the unit of work is an
    <strong>object</strong> rather than a single query tab. Each object sits at its own position and
    size and can overlap its neighbours. An object is one of five kinds today: a <strong>query</strong>
    that runs SQL and shows its rows, a <strong>chart</strong> that visualizes another query's
    results, a block of <strong>text</strong>, a <strong>sticky note</strong>, or a simple
    <strong>shape</strong>. The kinds are designed to grow, so more object types can be added later.
  </p>

  <p>
    The point of the board is to assemble an analysis you can see all at once: the query that pulls
    the data, the chart that makes it legible, and the commentary that explains it, side by side. You
    can build that by hand, but the fastest path is to ask the agent.
  </p>

  <h2 id="opening">Opening a canvas</h2>

  <p>
    Open a new board with the <strong>New Canvas</strong> button (the sparkles icon) in the editor
    tab bar, or run the <strong>New Canvas</strong> command from the keymap. A canvas opens as a
    center tab, just like a query or a notebook, and you can rename it. The board inherits the
    connection that is currently selected, so its query objects and the agent both target that
    database; pick a connection before creating the canvas if you want a specific one.
  </p>

  <h2 id="objects">Objects</h2>

  <DocTable>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Object</th>
        <th>What it does</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td class="font-medium text-fg">Query</td>
        <td>
          Holds one SQL statement with a <strong>Run</strong> button and a compact result grid. It
          runs against the canvas's connection, the same engine the editor uses.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="font-medium text-fg">Chart</td>
        <td>
          Visualizes a query object's results. A chart is bound to its source query, so when that
          query runs the chart updates. It uses the same chart engine as the results viewer.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="font-medium text-fg">Text</td>
        <td>Free text for headings and commentary. Double-click to edit in place.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="font-medium text-fg">Sticky note</td>
        <td>A coloured note for annotations, pinned on top of the board.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="font-medium text-fg">Shape</td>
        <td>
          A rectangle, ellipse, or line for grouping and annotation. Rectangles and
          ellipses hold optional centered text (double-click to add it), and a rectangle's
          corners can be rounded by dragging its radius handle.
        </td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </DocTable>

  <h2 id="agent">Building with the agent</h2>

  <p>
    The <strong>Agent</strong> panel runs down the left of the board. Type a request, for example
    <em>"monthly sales by category"</em>, and the agent reads the connection's schema and replies
    with a set of objects to add. A typical answer is a query object (the SQL that aggregates your
    data), a chart object bound to it, and a short text summary. Arris places the new objects on the
    board, runs the query automatically, and the chart renders from the result.
  </p>

  <p>
    Pick the provider in the chat header, the same <strong>Codex</strong> or <strong>Claude</strong>
    choice as the SQL agent (it is one shared preference). The agent runs that provider's local CLI
    under the same guardrails as the SQL agent: it runs locally in a read-only mode, never touches
    your filesystem,
    and only receives your prompt, the connection's <strong>schema as DDL</strong> and dialect, and a
    short summary of the objects already on the board (their kinds, ids, titles, and SQL), all capped
    in size. Your row data is not sent. Because the agent needs the schema to write correct SQL, the
    chat asks you to connect a database to the canvas first.
  </p>

  <p>
    Because each turn sees the current board, follow-up messages refine it in place rather than only
    piling on new objects. The agent can <strong>add</strong> any object kind (a query, chart, text
    block, sticky note, or shape), <strong>modify</strong> one that is already there (re-spec a chart
    as a line chart, rewrite a query, retitle an object), or <strong>remove</strong> objects you no
    longer want. A query the agent adds or changes runs automatically, and any chart bound to it
    updates.
  </p>

  <h2 id="board">Working on the board</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Add</strong> objects from the toolbar at the bottom of the board: a query, chart, sticky note, text, or shape. Tools with a caret open a small menu of options (the shape kind, the query language, the pointer mode).</li>
    <li><strong>Select</strong> an object with a single click; its resize anchors stay shown until you click an empty part of the board.</li>
    <li><strong>Adjust properties</strong> in the panel that opens on the right while one object is selected. Every object shows its position, size, and a lock toggle; below that each kind has its own controls (a shape's fill, stroke, and corner radius; a text block's font size, weight, alignment, and colour; a sticky note's tint; a query's title, connection, and Run; a chart's type, source query, and title).</li>
    <li><strong>Move</strong> an object by dragging it; objects may overlap. Text and sticky notes move on a single drag and open for editing on double-click. Switch the pointer to the <strong>Hand</strong> tool to pan the board from anywhere instead of dragging objects.</li>
    <li><strong>Resize</strong> a selected object by dragging any of its borders or corner handles.</li>
    <li><strong>Reorder, copy, and lock</strong> from an object's right-click menu: Copy duplicates it, the four restacking actions (Bring to front, Bring forward, Send backward, Send to back) change its overlap order, and Lock freezes it (a locked object can't be moved or resized until you unlock it).</li>
    <li><strong>Pan</strong> by dragging the empty canvas, and <strong>zoom</strong> with the scroll wheel or the controls in the corner.</li>
    <li><strong>Delete</strong> a selected object with <kbd>Delete</kbd> or <kbd>Backspace</kbd>.</li>
    <li><strong>Run</strong> a query object at any time with its Run button to refresh the charts bound to it.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="saving">Saving</h2>

  <p>
    A board is saved with your workspace, so it survives closing and reopening the tab and restarting
    Arris. Query results are not saved with the board; reopen a canvas and run its query objects to
    refresh the data.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
